To describe somewhere as "abandoned", it had to be quiet. The only noises heard in the abandoned is the dull stimulation of gravity, pushing objects against one another and cause the creaks and groans. The sound of passing time could be the only one in an abandoned place. The hum of still-powered HVAC systems and it's beating against crumbling vents had to be the only sounds you could hear while exploring.

What Clover was experiencing was <u>far</u> beyond that.

In this deprivation, even the silence was overbearing. The weight of stillness had grown stronger than anything else. Even as they put all the force their small legs could into stomping, the noise felt like it was pulled into the walls, never to bounce back. The audio was seemingly consumed by the rusted pillars over looking a grime-ridden sea. As Clover stepped towards the grated windows, their inky eyes scanned all they could see. 

[[File:GrimeSea.png|center|350px]]


Perfectly meeting Clover's expectation, they didn't see anything new. And looking behind them, it was the same stains of rusted metal. They ran their hand over the flakes of iron, pulling one off to look over it quietly. The tainted green crumbled in their fingers as Clover rubbed it between them. As it fell to their feet, Clover looked down the stairs that seemed to continually spiral. The steps blended into each other as their pattern continues. They fell silent as the lack of noise started to get to them again. It was a jarring stillness, screaming nothing yet still filling the room with its sound. 

"Just keep moving," Clover encouraged themself to start walking again, "eventually you'll find someone. Then it'll be ok."

Each step down filled the room with a cacophony for mere moments before it was muted again. A sick joke of a stairwell that they'd already spent 20 minutes walking down. Trying to keep their sanity by looking over each step became challenging and looking out through oceanic windows wasn't much better. Clover pressed themself against the wall as they merely glanced at the metal abyss between the stairs, it was an open gash in the metal piping; and with no stairwell barriers, looking down was easy as it was dreadful. At least further up, crooked turquoise chains seemed to slowly move down, following the pattern of the single wanderer. They didn't know why the chains stopped, but the metal binds seemed to connect one part of the structure to the one below it. All that metal with the perfect possibility of making noise, was silent. Even as Clover once shook the chains with all their might, the only noise was them swearing at themself when they cut their finger on the rusted chunks. Hopefully it isn't tetanus, the treatment for that probably doesn't even exist in the Backrooms.

As the descent continued, the empty space between the stairs was replaced by another set of chains. One continuous loop with two sections, one side slowly moving up, and the other, moving down. Each metal rung caught itself on the top and bottom of the shaft, connecting it to the subterranean walls. The setup was perfectly oriented so Clover would never hit one of the beams, yet it barely grazed their hair as they stepped below it. Perhaps anyone taller would hit their head against the metal. Clover was by no stretch of the imagination tall, and with just enough clearance for them, anyone else would likely be less lucky. 

Clover laughed a little at the thought. Those tiny moments of humanity brought much needed sanity to them as Clover deplaned into the steel-lined pit. 



<div style="border:5px solid #29b6f6; padding:10px 10px; margin:5em; background:black"><div style="border:3px solid #29b6f6; font-size:30px; font-family:New Amsterdam; text-align:center; padding:10px 20px">
Let us breathe in rusted tides

Taste replaces hearing

And makes sight strong again</div></div>



"Hey, hey!" 

The clicks of fingers against the palm failed to sway Clover, as their muffled senses caused only the clearest audio to reach them. Clover could hear the other's words, but wished not to interact with her. Instead they let their mind take over, as the soul seemed to separate itself to dance in its own realm of fastidious reality. An echo of the cold world around them. But as Clover's heart wandered off, something else had to be done about those around them.

[[File:Schoolhouse.png|center|350px]]


"God please shut up. For once in your life can you not spew spit?"

"Oh haha, you're the bitch who can't respond until I start screaming in your ear."

"I'm deaf." Clover turned lazily to look at Ava, letting their head fall onto one of their hands, both to shield one ear from the teen's tirade and to allow some way to rest after the day's lesson. Requiring both pretending to listen and watch a cheap translator made Clover's classwork admittedly poor. But for most teachers, they had grown familiar with Clover's difficulties and would provide other means to collect information. This teacher was the exception. A new educator who refused to ''bend over backwards'' for others. Which actually meant not support those with disabilities. 

How charming.

How honorable to not care for others. 

But this could be mitigated if Clover wasn't also faced with the frustration of group projects. A classic gripe among all peers, but it got worse those those they were paired with. Perhaps without surprise, this teacher paired them up with one of the most useless people they could think up. Supposedly these pairings were made to "challenge one another" but it turned into a game of who could force the other to do all the work. For some days it was Ava, others, it was Clover. All that existed between them was a tireless feud. Of course, Clover thought of themselves as the better person. But their mental games didn't much matter.

"That's no excuse to not do shit."

"When that ''shit'' is watching a video to summarize it to your partner, yes its an excuse. How the fuck do you think I'd be able to understand what was going on?"

"Closed captions?"

"Or, ''I'' could do the reading?"

Ava huffed and stood upright. Looking down at Clover with vague disgust. Her beach blonde hair and pale skin made Ava look like the babes in their father's magazines. Maybe their assumptions were unfounded, but Clover saw that same behavior in Ava, and it frustrated them all the same.

"I already said I'd do the reading and I was doing it." Ava insisted, looking out the window rather than to the eyes of her schoolwork partner. Not like it perturbed Clover, Clover didn't like looking at her either. "You're too late to claim to do it, so you just gotta suck it up and do it. I'm not getting a failing grade because you don't want to help me out." Ava separated herself from them, grabbing their bag and departing from the classroom. "I'll talk to you later. It better be done."

"Alright go fuck yourself too." Clover mumbled, watching the door close as they let their mind wander alongside their soul. As time raced by they remained unaware of it until they could feel their phone buzzing in their pocket. Clover pulled themself back into reality and looked at their phone. 


<big><center> 21:00 Curfew </center></big>


"Shit."



<div style="border:5px solid #29b6f6; padding:10px 10px; margin:5em; background:black"><div style="border:3px solid #29b6f6; font-size:30px; font-family:New Amsterdam; text-align:center; padding:10px 20px">
For whom does the schoolbell toll

A sound of sinking misery

Spiral downward through paper pounds</div></div>



It felt as Clover returned back to reality the stairs looked different. A new space that seemed to have slowly shifted from the previous one. Rusted steel shifted into wood, and the circular route became oblate. The what was oblate became rectangular and the rusted steel moved to the center of the stairs. Clover still had to keep going down, but the change of scenery gave them enough security to rest for a moment. The thud against the floor was still silent, with its muffling even harder to tell with Clover's shitty ears. However the lack of anything beyond that also signified that. They'd drop their bag of supplies by them, pulling out a protein bar. Chewing it was like swallowing chalk, and each bite made Clover a little less happy, but it was still nourishment. So they were left with no option but to swallow. 

Their eyes moved lazily around the wooden surfaces, before pressing down on the grated metallic stairs to rise again. They looked to the choked green fog, a hazy cover over anything beyond their grasp. As Clover turned their eyes up, celadon screen seemed to buzz awake, replacing their darkness with obscured text. It flashed by with twitching flickers, like code in the old hacking films. Oh how those frustrated Clover, and they weren't even familiar with whatever hacktivist group existed in the Backrooms. 

There wasn't a lot of time to process social bonds when getting through each level alive was enough of a challenge. At least, so far, Clover wasn't in danger in these subterranean spiral they found themselves in. And for a fleeting time, Clover felts safe enough to relax. Though on their feat, they pressed themself against a wall, humoring the belief of looking like a movie dame, lamenting about the loss of her hubby. Clover, was lamenting over their terrible choice in food. 

It was not long until Clover had a very rude awakening about their loneliness.

[[File:CeladonScreens.png|center|350px]]


But with little time to process, Clover heard the thundering of boots. A noise quickly muted but enough to catch as it was made. Clover felt their heart skip beats like a jazz performance. A bad one at that. The constricted sense of air they could feel if only for moments activated enough inside of Clover for them to start racing down steps again, panic set between their eyes as Clover fought their rationale. And lost. Heavily. 

The stairs of rusted metal clanged and went still again with each step, with no echo to support the chaotic descent. But as Clover picked up their pace, the other man seemed to as well. Perhaps aware of Clovers attempt to run. To even consider it was frightening enough for them, but the fact they acted on it only further triggered their pounding heart. The nuances blurred as Clover ran, lime coated televisions seemed to track them fine though. It was the encouragement they weren't looking for. Begging for Clover to go back and face their opposition. 

To look towards this change.



<div style="border:5px solid #29b6f6; padding:10px 10px; margin:5em; background:black"><div style="border:3px solid #29b6f6; font-size:30px; font-family:New Amsterdam; text-align:center; padding:10px 20px">
Falling down is the easiest commitment

But rising again provides the greatest challenge

To only live between is foolish</div></div>



 Meet me at the lighthouse


There were a lot of issues with the message. While Clover did know it was Ava, asking them to go to such a place felt unlike her. Clover didn't think about it for long though, as anything was better than being trapped in their home. 

"Imma go meet up for a project."

"Alright Clover, just come home before curfew."

"Sure, love you dad."

Clover left before their father could respond, hopping into their shoddy car to drive over. Each strange clunk Clover heard while driving they prayed they ran over a small child rather than their vehicle falling further apart. It was likely the latter, but they could hope otherwise, even if 30 small children couldn't be laying on the street at the same time. Maybe 2. Giving the neglectful parents the best benefit, Clover guess 5 of them were children. The rest, the death of a far more important object. 

The winds picked up around them as Clover parked in the the closet lot. Their wheels dug slightly into the grass, and the car's placement would be called "a good attempt" by her dad. But it didn't matter much, as they saw before them a tantalizing tower, gazing over a toothy maw of a cliff face. The ocean tide crashed against the rocky side. The sharp stone eroded to a fine point by a terminally stormy sea. Clover never remembered a day when it wasn't loud and volatile. Starkly contrasting the waves was the defunct lighthouse, its lights once a beacon for maritime travel now overshadowed by one only a few miles away. It stood alone, a reminder of its own former glory. Clover moved onward though, pushing through the wind and fickle rain softly pelting their coat. The tears of God brought wrath upon Clover, yet they refused to bend, gasping for a break as they pushed their way into the tower. 

"Welcome in!" Ava shouted. Well, Clover knew it was Ava, but she didn't sound the same. Clover could sense a change in her, and it left them conflicted. "Hurry up, I have things to tell you."

[[File:UptheLighthouse.png|center|350px]]


There wasn't any other option. And so, Clover climbed. As the reached the top of the tower, they looked at Ava. Was it Ava? Clover was pretty sure, but it has been a few years. But the change.. in only a few years? This wasn't Ava anymore, she was a different person. A different man. Ava looked oddly at Cloak, her head cocked to the side. "Are you alright?"

"No- yea. Yea I'm alright, what about you, you look so different." Ava laughed a little at that, it truly was a while since they last talked to each other. Even her annoying laugh was not as annoying. It was duller and more bassy, full of richer depths than Clover knew Ava to be capable of. Unable to make sense of it, they seemed to slip out of the tangible realm, mind slipping into a spiral of silent questions and concerns. 

"Yea.. that's why I asked you to meet up." Ava sighed and leaned on the rail, the sound of the storm still raging above them. But despite it, Ava seemed rather calm, the loud noise grew familiar to her over time. Whether by the chaos of life or the experience of education, Ava had become accustomed to anarchy. "I'm being forced to move after high school, Clover. My parents hate me now." Clover felt themself forced back into reality, their silent reflection of what they were told now trivial as they thought of a life spent without Ava. Someone they've grown up with now leaving. It left Clover stunned amid the cascading rain, not even the claps of thunder pulled them back. "So I'm going to tell you why."

"You fucking better."

"Yeah, yea. Well. I'm trans. Trans-masc." Ava laughed softly before muttering something, just loud enough for Clover to hear. "Thinking of changing my name to August or Austin..."

"...no way." Clover didn't intend their hatred, but they now were staring at a new person. This wasn't Ava anymore, it was a new man. Someone Clover didn't know. In their silence discovery, Ava mumbled something, but it seemed to get lost in their fickle mind. Clover did hear a month though, was it what Ava wanted to be now? It was the month of summer nights and bracing for September. Sun-kissed water and spray on tans. They couldn't commit it to memory though, as the silence from Ava as she left only seemed to certify their confusion.



<div style="border:5px solid #29b6f6; padding:10px 10px; margin:5em; background:black"><div style="border:3px solid #29b6f6; font-size:30px; font-family:New Amsterdam; text-align:center; padding:10px 20px">
The ups and down of life are constant

Change is infinity

And refuting it is the long way down</div></div>



"Holy shit are you ok?" Clover looked up to see the man chasing them down. They couldn't tell right away, but they were familiar. Pale skin paired with blonde hair, with dark streaks Clover swore they once saw. Their face was slender and bags were large, a faded red doused behind black sunglasses. The whisp of smoke from his breath struck their noise, alongside a melon scent. A scent of summer. He didn't wait for an answer from Clover, however. He moved one of Clover's arms over his shoulders and started their downward spiral again, slowly guiding them through each step. 

As Clover registered reality, they looked at him. They could feel a name on their tongue, but the words simply didn't want to leave.

[[File:MyManAugust.png|center|350px]]


{{Fullscreen
|padding=2rem
|number=1
|show="August?"
|hide= <span style="color:red">Go back</span>
|content={{Blurbackground|file=Black-Screen.png}}
<div style="margin:10em; text-align:center">
Clover watched August's eyes wash over with peace. He lost his stern look for one riddled with an elusive joy. It was a name he was hoping for Clover to remember, and seeing just that, was a reality he didn't want to let go of. For them, it was like a tension was lost the air seemed to soften as the man now became a familiar. Clover knew Ava, and if this was just Ava now, they were certain they could trust him. Clover gave August a soft smile as well.

"Yea, that's me. I'm happy you remember. How's it been?" 

"I should be asking you that, you look so much happier now." Clover spoke fast, their surprise unable to contain itself. It was a lively tone they forgot they had. The tribulations of the Backrooms seemed to pull those feelings away from them over time. But this seemed to give them hope, an unfamiliar feeling but a powerful one.

"Well, I got top surgery, and then ended up falling into the Backrooms."

"Same here, just without the surgery." August laughed, continuing to guide them down the stairs. While they didn't know what lied at the bottom rungs, but it seemed August did, and Clover had no issue trusting that. Clover and Augusts soft discussions continued as they reached a more familiar place. Somewhere safer.





Next tale: <s>Tides</s>
</div>}}


{{Fullscreen
|padding=2rem
|number=2
|show="Ava?"
|hide= <span style="color:red">Go back</span>
|content={{Blurbackground|file=Black-Screen.png}}
<div style="margin:10em; text-align:center">
Ava was left in silence, only responding with a soft nod. She looked Clover, trying to piece together something they didn't understand. To Ava, Clover had became an incomplete puzzle, just a symbol of something never solved. How could have they forgotten something so important to her? Either Clover simply forgot, or her fears were always true. Who would care about a stupid fuck like her? Ava couldn't show that anger through, so she forced a smile and shrugged idly.

"Yea, it's Ava. How have you been?"

"God it's been a journey." Clover began, their eyes lit up as they were finally given space to talk. They hadn't had the time to let everything go. And to do it with someone they knew well? It was liberating. Clover, starting with a sigh, exhausted both their voice and mind as they talked to Ava over all the events of life, and finding their way to the Backrooms. The journeys they went on, finally could be reiterated to someone they knew. She looked at Clover with nothing more intrigue, letting her conflictions dig their pits again as they talked to Clover. Ava asked about each journey in full, trying to ignore the pit that formed every time that old name was heard. 

A name Ava thought she killed. But dead names told tales still, and as they moved down each metal step, Ava was faced with a musical of dead words.





